  • Sarah F
    5 contributions
    Beautiful and walkable city. If you're driving up, I'd recommend staying in the St. Roch area because there are a lot of airbnbs that have free parking. I suggest exploring Old Quebec city without a tour since its not really a big city-I loved petit-champlain and the Place Royal. They are both great places to take pictures. Lunch at Cafe La Maison Smith (there are two in Old Quebec but I recommend going to the one in Place Royal for a pretty view at lunch) and dessert at Chocolato in petit-champlain. The Plains of Abraham and the citadel were great sites to see. Going on the big toboggan slide by the Chateau Frontenac was also so much fun and only $5 a ticket. I recommend going during the week because the line is pretty long on the weekend. In Saint Roch I LOVED Hono Ramen-definitely the best restaurant I went to on this trip. The quail eggs and miso ramen were delicious. The saint-jean baptiste neighborhood is also worth a visit-if you like crepes, I recommend Le Billig Creperie-Bistro. I also suggest staying for 4 nights since Quebec city isn't that big.
    Review of: Old Quebec

  • Gretagerm
    Montgomery, Texas53 contributions
    Lovely continental vibe in old Quebec! We feel we just went to France without leaving North America. Walking the cobblestone streets, appreciating the stately architecture and enjoying the ambiance of Quebec was a delight on so many levels. Art galleries abound along with cozy bistros. Eat any type of food from Italian to French to Indian or middle Eastern and of course American food street side or inside air conditioned cafes. You never feel rushed when enjoying a good coffee or glass of wine as you watch passerbys. Nearly everyone in the tourist areas speaks English but smaller areas are largely French only. Time to use Google translate if you have lost your mastery of high school French! A cheery bonjour! offered as a greeting as you interact with the locals will immediately be recognized by your accent that they should continue in English. But they appreciate your effort to greet them in French! Also appreciated is a French “thank you”! Merci! Hop on hop off buses take you past ancient landmarks while local guides relate the history and highlights of the city. Our hotel was quiet, with two foot thick stone walls. It housed a lovely off the street courtyard, a beautiful room for breakfast. Multiple fireplaces once used exclusively to heat the separate rooms enhance the experience. Visit the Chateau Frontenac where you’ll find high end shops, works ambiance and formal dining venues. High tea there is a world class experience. We found prices reasonable particularly since the American dollar can buy 1.4 Canadian dollars worth of goods! We left vowing to return and explore even more of the old city in the very near future.
    Review of: Old Quebec

  • hnre
    684 contributions
    Old Quebec City is particularly well-suited for walking. It is recommended to wear comfortable shoes, as you will be on your feet for extended periods. The terrain includes several steep slopes, avoid footwear with slick soles. In the event of light rain, you may find yourself sliding down the hill. When checking the weather during the summer months, pay attention to the humidity levels. During our visit, we experienced both heat and humidity. The area is a popular destination for tourists. Be sure to visit the historical landmarks. If history does not capture your interest, there are numerous cafes that offer delightful croissants. To my surprise, there is also a McDonald's and a Subway in the vicinity. Additionally, there is a gelato shop (I forgot the name), although it is quite expensive for a small scoop.

  • BigJeff L
    2,564 contributions
    Old Quebec City is broadly split into the upper and lower towns. The Upper Town, built on the cliff, has remained the religious and administrative centre, with its churches, convents and other monuments like the Dauphine Redoubt, the Citadel and the amazing Château Frontenac. Together with the Lower Town and its ancient districts, it forms an urban center which is one of the best examples of a fortified colonial city. It is the only North American city to have preserved its ramparts, walls and gates. Old Quebec is made for walking. The city’s ancient streets are narrow, winding, and contain so many treasures including shops, places to eat and wonderful architecture. The city is proud of its history and for me it is simply one of Canada's highlights.
    Review of: Old Quebec

Comfortable walking shoes are essential because of the ups and downs
Dec 2024 • Solo
It was the most European townscape in North America, but compared to the European townscape, I thought, well, this is what it looks like. To be sure, it has a very European look to it, but I might have expected too much.
The old town has two towns, Upper Town and Lower Town, but I thought it was hard to walk around because there were hills everywhere in the upper town.
Especially in winter, the roads were icy and I felt that I could get hurt if I didn't walk carefully. Upper Town and Lower Town have several buses, so you might want to consider bus travel (although it's a hassle to have limited places to buy tickets)

What to do with children in Quebec City?
Written November 18, 2023
GrandTour452506
503 contributions
I would say it depends on the age and interest of the kids. You could walk the Duffin Terrace and go west to the Citadel and Plains of Abraham. The views from there are really cool. There is a lot of history there to be learned. On the way up if you walk up you can visit Montmorency historical park. All of these places are very walkable. They also have plaques in both French and English talking about the history of the area. You can catch some of the murals around town too.
